WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.00 --> 00:00:00.84


00:00:00.84 --> 00:00:03.61
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:03.61 --> 00:00:08.46


00:00:08.46 --> 00:00:11.97
Now to disturbing new data from Crowdstrike, one of the leading

00:00:11.97 --> 00:00:13.41
cybersecurity firms--

00:00:13.41 --> 00:00:18.36
its Eighth Annual Global Threat Report detected a whopping 82%

00:00:18.36 --> 00:00:21.42
spike worldwide in ransomware-linked data

00:00:21.42 --> 00:00:22.20
breaches.

00:00:22.20 --> 00:00:24.96
The report introduces potential new hacking groups

00:00:24.96 --> 00:00:27.54
and explains how attacks are getting

00:00:27.54 --> 00:00:29.73
increasingly sophisticated.

00:00:29.73 --> 00:00:32.73
Plus, it offers intricate details on the latest tactics

00:00:32.73 --> 00:00:34.95
employed by the so-called big four--

00:00:34.95 --> 00:00:38.28
Iran, China, Russia, and North Korea.

00:00:38.28 --> 00:00:40.47
Here to detail the report is Adam Meyers.

00:00:40.47 --> 00:00:42.87
He's Crowdstrike's head of intelligence.

00:00:42.87 --> 00:00:44.77
Adam, good to have you joining us.

00:00:44.77 --> 00:00:46.62
So tell us, what are the big takeaways

00:00:46.62 --> 00:00:49.65
from this year's report?

00:00:49.65 --> 00:00:50.65
Well, there was a bunch.

00:00:50.65 --> 00:00:54.13
I think the first one is that we identified that

00:00:54.13 --> 00:00:57.61
about 98 minutes from the time that a bad actor, a threat

00:00:57.61 --> 00:01:00.46
actor gets onto a system till they can move deeper

00:01:00.46 --> 00:01:03.07
into a network and get access to sensitive data

00:01:03.07 --> 00:01:04.39
and sensitive systems.

00:01:04.39 --> 00:01:08.05
That means that defenders only have about 98 minutes that they

00:01:08.05 --> 00:01:13.93
can identify and investigate and then repel or defend

00:01:13.93 --> 00:01:15.24
against that attack.

00:01:15.24 --> 00:01:16.03
That's interesting.

00:01:16.03 --> 00:01:19.96
When you think about it in terms of a more traditional crime,

00:01:19.96 --> 00:01:22.06
like a bank robbery, the idea that it only

00:01:22.06 --> 00:01:24.58
takes 98 minutes for them to get in

00:01:24.58 --> 00:01:27.01
and get out and have all that they need

00:01:27.01 --> 00:01:28.90
to perpetrate their attacks.

00:01:28.90 --> 00:01:30.37
Give us some context, though, Adam.

00:01:30.37 --> 00:01:32.86
How many ransomware attacks were there last year

00:01:32.86 --> 00:01:36.18
compared to previous years?

00:01:36.18 --> 00:01:39.69
It was up about 36%, I believe, last year

00:01:39.69 --> 00:01:40.71
over the previous year.

00:01:40.71 --> 00:01:44.37
But one of the more interesting things that we identified

00:01:44.37 --> 00:01:48.36
was that there was an 82% increase in data extortion

00:01:48.36 --> 00:01:50.88
attacks, where they not only encrypt the data,

00:01:50.88 --> 00:01:54.18
but they steal it and then hold that hostage or hold it ransom.

00:01:54.18 --> 00:01:56.91
And this is a growing trend that we've

00:01:56.91 --> 00:02:00.66
seen of weaponization of data, where victim data is

00:02:00.66 --> 00:02:01.96
being used against them.

00:02:01.96 --> 00:02:03.57
It's being used as a control lever

00:02:03.57 --> 00:02:07.74
to force them to pay higher ransoms, to pay faster.

00:02:07.74 --> 00:02:10.50
And it's being used by nation-states as well.

00:02:10.50 --> 00:02:13.17
Tell us, then, what's that staggering increase?

00:02:13.17 --> 00:02:16.59
I mean, we have heard more reports of both big companies

00:02:16.59 --> 00:02:20.76
and individuals being targeted in these types of extortion

00:02:20.76 --> 00:02:22.99
attacks.

00:02:22.99 --> 00:02:24.53
Yeah, lots of people have identified.

00:02:24.53 --> 00:02:27.03
It's a problem that's been going on for a number of years.

00:02:27.03 --> 00:02:29.42
So we encounter more and more organizations

00:02:29.42 --> 00:02:32.09
that have really robust backup solutions that

00:02:32.09 --> 00:02:34.34
enable them to recover from these ransomware attacks

00:02:34.34 --> 00:02:35.49
pretty quickly.

00:02:35.49 --> 00:02:38.30
But when the data is stolen and leaked to the internet,

00:02:38.30 --> 00:02:39.74
there's no backup solution that's

00:02:39.74 --> 00:02:41.58
going to stop that or help you there.

00:02:41.58 --> 00:02:44.22
And if you think the ransom demand is high,

00:02:44.22 --> 00:02:48.86
the legal fees, the regulatory and compliance issues

00:02:48.86 --> 00:02:50.90
that come from that data being stolen and leaked

00:02:50.90 --> 00:02:53.18
to the internet can add up very quickly

00:02:53.18 --> 00:02:57.71
and really just be massive compared to that ransom demand

00:02:57.71 --> 00:02:58.86
itself.

00:02:58.86 --> 00:03:01.52
So given all of that, given how quickly it moves,

00:03:01.52 --> 00:03:08.75
given how people seem to be paying out these extortion

00:03:08.75 --> 00:03:14.21
threats, that's led to more and more of these types of attacks

00:03:14.21 --> 00:03:15.56
being perpetrated.

00:03:15.56 --> 00:03:17.48
What can people do to stay safe?

00:03:17.48 --> 00:03:20.40


00:03:20.40 --> 00:03:23.51
One of the things that has been a huge differentiator

00:03:23.51 --> 00:03:25.64
over the last year that I've personally witnessed

00:03:25.64 --> 00:03:29.09
is employing things like identity management and zero

00:03:29.09 --> 00:03:29.60
trust.

00:03:29.60 --> 00:03:31.22
What this really allows you to do

00:03:31.22 --> 00:03:34.01
is not just protect the system, but protect the data

00:03:34.01 --> 00:03:35.97
and protect access to the data.

00:03:35.97 --> 00:03:39.65
So if there's one thing that people would do, particularly

00:03:39.65 --> 00:03:42.20
at the enterprise level, to better defend against this,

00:03:42.20 --> 00:03:43.85
it's to employ things like zero trust,

00:03:43.85 --> 00:03:45.59
to have strong identity management,

00:03:45.59 --> 00:03:48.38
and protect the data, not just the systems.

00:03:48.38 --> 00:03:52.03
All right, Adam Meyers, thank you so much.

00:03:52.03 --> 00:03:53.75
Thank you.